{"repo": "dask/distributed", "pull_number": 9195, "instance_id": "dask__distributed-9195", "issue_numbers": [8490], "base_commit": "4fb4814bcf0015445f2cfe82487591bf1553ac2c", "patch": "diff --git a/distributed/dashboard/components/scheduler.py b/distributed/dashboard/components/scheduler.py\nindex 859c55c57a0..31224d5c12a 100644\n--- a/distributed/dashboard/components/scheduler.py\n+++ b/distributed/dashboard/components/scheduler.py\n@@ -4076,6 +4076,7 @@ def __init__(self, scheduler, **kwargs):\n             \"host_disk_io.read_bps\",\n             \"host_disk_io.write_bps\",\n             \"cpu_fraction\",\n+            \"_is_total\",\n         ]\n         workers = self.scheduler.workers.values()\n         self.extra_names = sorted(\n@@ -4128,7 +4129,14 @@ def __init__(self, scheduler, **kwargs):\n         }\n \n         formatters = {\n-            \"cpu\": NumberFormatter(format=\"0 %\"),\n+            # Use a pure number (0 to nthreads) on the total line and a %\n+            # (e.g. 0 to 400% for 4 threads per worker ) on the individual workers.\n+            # It would be very confusing to read e.g. 9000% on the total, whereas\n+            # seeing that ~90 CPU equivalents are being fully used is more meaningful.\n+            \"cpu\": HTMLTemplateFormatter(\n+                template=\"<% if (_is_total) { %><%= (value).toFixed(1) %>\"\n+                \"<% } else { %><%= Math.round(value * 100) %> %<% } %>\"\n+            ),\n             \"memory_percent\": NumberFormatter(format=\"0.0 %\"),\n             \"memory\": NumberFormatter(format=\"0.0 b\"),\n             \"memory_limit\": NumberFormatter(format=\"0.0 b\"),\n@@ -4281,11 +4289,15 @@ def update(self):\n             data[\"cpu\"][-1] = ws.metrics[\"cpu\"] / 100.0\n             data[\"cpu_fraction\"][-1] = ws.metrics[\"cpu\"] / 100.0 / ws.nthreads\n             data[\"nthreads\"][-1] = ws.nthreads\n+            data[\"_is_total\"][-1] = False\n \n         for name in self.names + self.extra_names:\n             if name == \"name\":\n                 data[name].insert(0, f\"Total ({len(data[name])})\")\n                 continue\n+            if name == \"_is_total\":\n+                data[name].insert(0, True)\n+                continue\n             try:\n                 if len(self.scheduler.workers) == 0:\n                     total_data = None\n@@ -4308,7 +4320,6 @@ def update(self):\n                     total_data = (\n                         sum(ws.metrics[\"cpu\"] for ws in self.scheduler.workers.values())\n                         / 100\n-                        / len(self.scheduler.workers.values())\n                     )\n                 elif name == \"cpu_fraction\":\n                     total_data = (\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/distributed/dashboard/tests/test_scheduler_bokeh.py b/distributed/dashboard/tests/test_scheduler_bokeh.py\nindex bf2f8430282..2836e4fa75f 100644\n--- a/distributed/dashboard/tests/test_scheduler_bokeh.py\n+++ b/distributed/dashboard/tests/test_scheduler_bokeh.py\n@@ -564,6 +564,17 @@ async def test_WorkerTable(c, s, a, b):\n     assert all(nthreads)\n     assert nthreads[0] == nthreads[1] + nthreads[2]\n \n+    # Total CPU should show raw core count (sum of all worker CPU / 100)\n+    cpu = wt.source.data[\"cpu\"]\n+    expected_cpu_total = sum(ws.metrics[\"cpu\"] for ws in s.workers.values()) / 100\n+    assert cpu[0] == expected_cpu_total\n+\n+    # _is_total flag should be set correctly\n+    is_total = wt.source.data[\"_is_total\"]\n+    assert is_total[0] is True\n+    assert is_total[1] is False\n+    assert is_total[2] is False\n+\n \n @gen_cluster(client=True)\n async def test_WorkerTable_custom_metrics(c, s, a, b):\n", "problem_statement": "Total CPU % on /workers tab makes little sense\nFrom https://dask.discourse.group/t/dask-worker-using-600-of-the-cpu/2489/2\r\n\r\nThe CPU % on each individual worker scales from 0 to nthreads*100; e.g. on a worker with 8 threads it can go from 0% to 800%. This is coherent with several other CPU monitors in the wild so it makes sense.\r\n\r\nThe CPU% on the Total row, however, is calculated as \r\nhttps://github.com/dask/distributed/blob/4425516f86d7de9aed06053fc3e21a17fe20efc4/distributed/dashboard/components/scheduler.py#L4303-L4308\r\n\r\nSo for example on a cluster with 2 workers, 8 threads per worker, if one worker is flat out busy while the other is idle, the Total will be 400%, which makes very little sense.\r\n\r\n| name | nthreads | cpu |\r\n| --- | --- | --- |\r\nTotal (2) | 16 | 400% |\r\ntcp://... | 8 | 800% |\r\ntcp://... | 8 | 0% |\r\n\r\nI think we should change the CPU% on each worker to go from 0 to 100% and that on the total line to do the same (total CPU usage across the cluster / total number of threads)\r\nIn the above example, that would become\r\n\r\n| name | nthreads | cpu |\r\n| --- | --- | --- |\r\nTotal (2) | 16 | 50% |\r\ntcp://... | 8 | 100% |\r\ntcp://... | 8 | 0% |\r\n\n", "hints_text": "I'm a bit torn here:\r\n\r\nOn the one hand, summing the CPU usage up feels useful for a single worker. For example, being stuck at 100% might indicate that we're not able to effectively use our multi-core CPUs. Being stuck at 12.5% (on an 8-core machine) feels less useful, in particular, since we don't ever tell you the number of cores on your machine. \r\n\r\nOn the other hand, summing the CPU usage up makes the total meaningless very quickly, in particular on an adaptive cluster. (Cool, CPU usage is >9000%....what does that even mean?)\r\n\r\nThere are a few alternatives that come to mind: \r\n* Sum everything up, but provide an upper bound `400% (800%)` (presentation is TBD).\r\n* Collect the CPU statistics per CPU (`psutil.cpu_percent(percpu=True)`) and calculate some truly meaningful statistics, e.g., `min`, `max`, `mean`, `median`, `20/80 pct`, etc.\n- xref https://github.com/dask/distributed/pull/3897\nI'd like to work on this. The fix is straightforward \u2014 the Total CPU % calculation at `scheduler.py:L4311` divides by `len(workers)` instead of `sum(nthreads)`, producing incorrect values when workers have multiple threads. The `cpu_fraction` column already uses the correct divisor (`sum(ws.nthreads)`), so the `cpu` column just needs to match. This is the same pattern as PR #3897, which fixed the identical bug for `memory_percent`. Will submit a PR shortly.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "I'm a bit torn here:\r\n\r\nOn the one hand, summing the CPU usage up feels useful for a single worker. For example, being stuck at 100% might indicate that we're not able to effectively use our multi-core CPUs. Being stuck at 12.5% (on an 8-core machine) feels less useful, in particular, since we don't ever tell you the number of cores on your machine. \r\n\r\nOn the other hand, summing the CPU usage up makes the total meaningless very quickly, in particular on an adaptive cluster. (Cool, CPU usage is >9000%....what does that even mean?)\r\n\r\nThere are a few alternatives that come to mind: \r\n* Sum everything up, but provide an upper bound `400% (800%)` (presentation is TBD).\r\n* Collect the CPU statistics per CPU (`psutil.cpu_percent(percpu=True)`) and calculate some truly meaningful statistics, e.g., `min`, `max`, `mean`, `median`, `20/80 pct`, etc.\n- xref https://github.com/dask/distributed/pull/3897\nI'd like to work on this. The fix is straightforward \u2014 the Total CPU % calculation at `scheduler.py:L4311` divides by `len(workers)` instead of `sum(nthreads)`, producing incorrect values when workers have multiple threads. The `cpu_fraction` column already uses the correct divisor (`sum(ws.nthreads)`), so the `cpu` column just needs to match. This is the same pattern as PR #3897, which fixed the identical bug for `memory_percent`. Will submit a PR shortly.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/28c7c52169926fb5f3c4ece1cd70b6ef9eb8a33c", "https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/1fe4af22faaa81c8193aaff343fd6f6c0a89afb7", "https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/5ac5b2644fa3663e3b2abe1856c1a4897466419c", "https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/5fcaa6c063ac17dbc9a9d0178ada5d00cf375d36"], "created_at": "2026-02-22T14:40:03Z"}
{"repo": "dask/distributed", "pull_number": 9069, "instance_id": "dask__distributed-9069", "issue_numbers": [8614], "base_commit": "beb511bbdff8d88868cab46d6d2856b3ce466685", "patch": "diff --git a/continuous_integration/environment-3.10.yaml b/continuous_integration/environment-3.10.yaml\nindex 5b8b21d02dd..03cc7527503 100644\n--- a/continuous_integration/environment-3.10.yaml\n+++ b/continuous_integration/environment-3.10.yaml\n@@ -13,7 +13,7 @@ dependencies:\n   - coverage\n   - cython  # Only tested here; also a dependency of crick\n   - dask  # overridden by git tip below\n-  - filesystem-spec  # overridden by git tip below\n+  - fsspec\n   - gilknocker\n   - h5py\n   - ipykernel\n@@ -41,7 +41,7 @@ dependencies:\n   - python-snappy  # Only tested here\n   - pytorch  # Only tested here\n   - requests\n-  - s3fs  # overridden by git tip below\n+  - s3fs\n   - scikit-learn\n   - scipy\n   - sortedcollections\n@@ -59,7 +59,4 @@ dependencies:\n       - git+https://github.com/dask/dask\n       - git+https://github.com/dask/zict\n       - git+https://github.com/dask/crick  # Only tested here\n-      # Revert after https://github.com/dask/distributed/issues/8614 is fixed\n-      # - git+https://github.com/dask/s3fs\n-      # - git+https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec\n       - keras\ndiff --git a/continuous_integration/environment-3.11.yaml b/continuous_integration/environment-3.11.yaml\nindex ae136e17387..e0cf65f1fa0 100644\n--- a/continuous_integration/environment-3.11.yaml\n+++ b/continuous_integration/environment-3.11.yaml\n@@ -12,7 +12,7 @@ dependencies:\n   - cloudpickle\n   - coverage\n   - dask  # overridden by git tip below\n-  - filesystem-spec  # overridden by git tip below\n+  - fsspec  # overridden by git tip below\n   - gilknocker\n   - h5py\n   - ipykernel\n@@ -52,7 +52,6 @@ dependencies:\n   - pip:\n       - git+https://github.com/dask/dask\n       - git+https://github.com/dask/zict\n-      # Revert after https://github.com/dask/distributed/issues/8614 is fixed\n-      # - git+https://github.com/dask/s3fs\n-      # - git+https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec\n+      - git+https://github.com/dask/s3fs\n+      - git+https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec\n       - keras\ndiff --git a/continuous_integration/environment-3.12.yaml b/continuous_integration/environment-3.12.yaml\nindex bd37fbf4042..a038128e0f4 100644\n--- a/continuous_integration/environment-3.12.yaml\n+++ b/continuous_integration/environment-3.12.yaml\n@@ -12,7 +12,7 @@ dependencies:\n   - cloudpickle\n   - coverage\n   - dask  # overridden by git tip below\n-  - filesystem-spec  # overridden by git tip below\n+  - fsspec  # overridden by git tip below\n   - gilknocker\n   - h5py\n   - ipykernel\n@@ -52,7 +52,6 @@ dependencies:\n   - pip:\n       - git+https://github.com/dask/dask\n       - git+https://github.com/dask/zict\n-      # Revert after https://github.com/dask/distributed/issues/8614 is fixed\n-      # - git+https://github.com/dask/s3fs\n-      # - git+https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec\n+      - git+https://github.com/dask/s3fs\n+      - git+https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec\n       - keras\ndiff --git a/continuous_integration/environment-3.13.yaml b/continuous_integration/environment-3.13.yaml\nindex a60f216f996..958e9aa3f48 100644\n--- a/continuous_integration/environment-3.13.yaml\n+++ b/continuous_integration/environment-3.13.yaml\n@@ -11,7 +11,7 @@ dependencies:\n   - cloudpickle\n   - coverage\n   - dask  # overridden by git tip below\n-  - filesystem-spec  # overridden by git tip below\n+  - fsspec  # overridden by git tip below\n   - gilknocker\n   - h5py\n   - ipykernel\n@@ -51,7 +51,6 @@ dependencies:\n   - pip:\n       - git+https://github.com/dask/dask\n       - git+https://github.com/dask/zict\n-      # Revert after https://github.com/dask/distributed/issues/8614 is fixed\n-      # - git+https://github.com/dask/s3fs\n-      # - git+https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec\n+      - git+https://github.com/dask/s3fs\n+      - git+https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec\n       - keras\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "CI failure due to dependency conflict\nAll our CI jobs with python>3.10 are failing due to a dependency resolution conflict\r\n\r\n\r\n```\r\nThe conflict is caused by:\r\n    The user requested fsspec 2024.3.2.dev5+g2dd9355 (from git+https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec)\r\n    dask 2024.4.1+4.gb2ec1e1a depends on fsspec>=2021.09.0\r\n    s3fs 2024.3.1+2.g7ccc0a5 depends on fsspec==2024.3.1\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\ncc @martindurant are you aware of anything that caused this hard pinning between s3fs and fsspec?\r\n\r\ne.g. https://github.com/dask/distributed/actions/runs/8619396892/job/23704420478?pr=8610\n", "hints_text": "Yes, s3fs (and gcsfs) are hard pinned to exactly the same version as fsspec, and have been for a long time. They are always released within hours of each other.\r\n\r\nThe latest release is 2024.3.1. I am thinking that the introduction of hatch in https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec/pull/1553 has caused the dev version to be called \"2024.3.2.XXX\" instead of \"2024.3.1.XXX\" as versioneer used to do. I am not sure how to change this convention. \nOK, I don't want our entire CI to be blocked by this and opened https://github.com/dask/distributed/pull/8615 to temporarily just run CI against stable versions until this is figured out\nhttps://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec/pull/1569 should fix this, if you care to try\n#8618 tries this\nPlease try again with main/master whenever you think the caches might have cleared. \ndid that on my revert pr\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Yes, s3fs (and gcsfs) are hard pinned to exactly the same version as fsspec, and have been for a long time. They are always released within hours of each other.\r\n\r\nThe latest release is 2024.3.1. I am thinking that the introduction of hatch in https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec/pull/1553 has caused the dev version to be called \"2024.3.2.XXX\" instead of \"2024.3.1.XXX\" as versioneer used to do. I am not sure how to change this convention. \nOK, I don't want our entire CI to be blocked by this and opened https://github.com/dask/distributed/pull/8615 to temporarily just run CI against stable versions until this is figured out\nhttps://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec/pull/1569 should fix this, if you care to try\n#8618 tries this\nPlease try again with main/master whenever you think the caches might have cleared. \ndid that on my revert pr\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/58beb4d6bb4e2e9d334aac619b650e1cdfd3418f", "https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/b66ac7f35cfd1843c95d5e6cd0bf22318d5937c8"], "created_at": "2025-05-06T15:39:37Z"}
{"repo": "dask/distributed", "pull_number": 9109, "instance_id": "dask__distributed-9109", "issue_numbers": [9055], "base_commit": "7024d521bb2947bd4a8a713648b2e41b134f98b5", "patch": "diff --git a/distributed/dashboard/components/scheduler.py b/distributed/dashboard/components/scheduler.py\nindex 75c10d1fcfa..fe6566bf479 100644\n--- a/distributed/dashboard/components/scheduler.py\n+++ b/distributed/dashboard/components/scheduler.py\n@@ -25,6 +25,7 @@\n     ColumnDataSource,\n     CustomJSHover,\n     DataRange1d,\n+    DatetimeTickFormatter,\n     FactorRange,\n     GroupFilter,\n     HelpTool,\n@@ -52,6 +53,7 @@\n from bokeh.themes import Theme\n from bokeh.transform import cumsum, factor_cmap, linear_cmap, stack\n from jinja2 import Environment, FileSystemLoader\n+from packaging.version import parse as parse_version\n from tlz import curry, pipe, second, valmap\n from tlz.curried import concat, groupby, map\n \n@@ -76,6 +78,7 @@\n )\n from distributed.dashboard.utils import (\n     _DATATABLE_STYLESHEETS_KWARGS,\n+    BOKEH_VERSION,\n     PROFILING,\n     transpose,\n     update,\n@@ -2192,7 +2195,9 @@ def task_stream_figure(clear_interval=\"20s\", **kwargs):\n         x_range=x_range,\n         y_range=y_range,\n         toolbar_location=\"above\",\n-        x_axis_type=\"datetime\",\n+        x_axis_type=(\n+            \"timedelta\" if BOKEH_VERSION >= parse_version(\"3.8.0\") else \"datetime\"\n+        ),\n         y_axis_location=None,\n         tools=\"\",\n         min_border_bottom=50,\n@@ -2216,6 +2221,12 @@ def task_stream_figure(clear_interval=\"20s\", **kwargs):\n     root.yaxis.major_label_text_alpha = 0\n     root.yaxis.minor_tick_line_alpha = 0\n     root.yaxis.major_tick_line_alpha = 0\n+    if BOKEH_VERSION < parse_version(\"3.8.0\") and BOKEH_VERSION >= parse_version(\n+        \"3.5.2\"\n+    ):\n+        root.xaxis[0].formatter = DatetimeTickFormatter(\n+            boundary_scaling=False, context=None\n+        )  # remove full date context misleading for users\n     root.xgrid.visible = False\n \n     hover = HoverTool(\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Task Stream dashboard now showing date\n<img width=\"527\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/00fac7e5-af6f-4b55-8f07-d4007f5b3599\" />\n\nIdeally we'd want just the time.  \n\nI suspect that this is due to a Bokeh update\n", "hints_text": "I am running distributed 2025.7.0 and bokeh 3.7.3 and  I noticed that in system page\n\n<img width=\"794\" height=\"650\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/badbd5b0-7670-4641-9307-0a0e7fbb8619\" />\n\nand in profile page\n\n<img width=\"966\" height=\"651\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2d6e3389-fc68-41c3-bbc3-a7471ed6f1e2\" />\n\ndate are correct, but in task page and in status page, the date is 1970\n\n<img width=\"1256\" height=\"836\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/950f6422-c53f-4c50-ba7c-45bf3f120605\" />\n\n\nlikely beause in the timestamp of WS payload received is 0\nHi there, I tried looking at the Dashboard code or Bokeh documentation, but I don't really see where to start. Ideally there would be some argument in bokeh to render date without the day, the other more complicated solution will be to give real timestamps to the payload. Any pointer on how to do any of this?\n\n** edit **\n\nI think a solution for the first option would be to customize a [DatetimeTickFormatter ](https://docs.bokeh.org/en/latest/docs/reference/models/formatters.html#bokeh.models.DatetimeTickFormatter), and removing first context.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "I am running distributed 2025.7.0 and bokeh 3.7.3 and  I noticed that in system page\n\n<img width=\"794\" height=\"650\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/badbd5b0-7670-4641-9307-0a0e7fbb8619\" />\n\nand in profile page\n\n<img width=\"966\" height=\"651\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2d6e3389-fc68-41c3-bbc3-a7471ed6f1e2\" />\n\ndate are correct, but in task page and in status page, the date is 1970\n\n<img width=\"1256\" height=\"836\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/950f6422-c53f-4c50-ba7c-45bf3f120605\" />\n\n\nlikely beause in the timestamp of WS payload received is 0\nHi there, I tried looking at the Dashboard code or Bokeh documentation, but I don't really see where to start. Ideally there would be some argument in bokeh to render date without the day, the other more complicated solution will be to give real timestamps to the payload. Any pointer on how to do any of this?\n\n** edit **\n\nI think a solution for the first option would be to customize a [DatetimeTickFormatter ](https://docs.bokeh.org/en/latest/docs/reference/models/formatters.html#bokeh.models.DatetimeTickFormatter), and removing first context.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/77771988000663b3f9753e5c23d3ff5778527cb5", "https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/331e13794a820895456f09db541e89a9bd9dd331", "https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/1f69e4d2d3253f906286c5115d5f4a2c757ac5b9", "https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/7d57803d6f5babd516e5b5aaebf12a260c9f86c7"], "created_at": "2025-09-10T14:23:06Z"}
{"repo": "dask/distributed", "pull_number": 9066, "instance_id": "dask__distributed-9066", "issue_numbers": [9065], "base_commit": "f56b02e50d83d93a9925ed95ac56d388c4374f88", "patch": "diff --git a/distributed/client.py b/distributed/client.py\nindex bfcce5bc703..e758fb5bee6 100644\n--- a/distributed/client.py\n+++ b/distributed/client.py\n@@ -1343,18 +1343,16 @@ def __repr__(self):\n         info = self._scheduler_identity\n         addr = info.get(\"address\")\n         if addr:\n-            workers = info.get(\"workers\", {})\n-            nworkers = len(workers)\n-            nthreads = sum(w[\"nthreads\"] for w in workers.values())\n+            nworkers = info.get(\"n_workers\", 0)\n+            nthreads = info.get(\"total_threads\", 0)\n             text = \"<%s: %r processes=%d threads=%d\" % (\n                 self.__class__.__name__,\n                 addr,\n                 nworkers,\n                 nthreads,\n             )\n-            memory = [w[\"memory_limit\"] for w in workers.values()]\n-            if all(memory):\n-                text += \", memory=\" + format_bytes(sum(memory))\n+            memory = info.get(\"total_memory\", 0)\n+            text += \", memory=\" + format_bytes(memory)\n             text += \">\"\n             return text\n \n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/distributed/tests/test_client.py b/distributed/tests/test_client.py\nindex aa7f8fa84c6..378a3c48142 100644\n--- a/distributed/tests/test_client.py\n+++ b/distributed/tests/test_client.py\n@@ -2118,12 +2118,21 @@ async def test_badly_serialized_input_stderr(capsys, c):\n     ],\n )\n def test_repr(loop, func):\n-    with cluster(nworkers=3, worker_kwargs={\"memory_limit\": \"2 GiB\"}) as (s, [a, b, c]):\n+    nworkers = 6\n+    with cluster(nworkers=nworkers, worker_kwargs={\"memory_limit\": \"2 GiB\"}) as (\n+        s,\n+        *workers,\n+    ):\n         with Client(s[\"address\"], loop=loop) as c:\n+            # NOTE: Intentionally testing when we have more workers than the default\n+            # in `client.scheduler_info()` (xref https://github.com/dask/distributed/issues/9065)\n+            info = c.scheduler_info()\n+            assert len(info[\"workers\"]) < nworkers\n+\n             text = func(c)\n             assert c.scheduler.address in text\n-            assert \"threads=3\" in text or \"Total threads: </strong>\" in text\n-            assert \"6.00 GiB\" in text\n+            assert f\"threads={nworkers}\" in text or \"Total threads: </strong>\" in text\n+            assert f\"{2 * nworkers}.00 GiB\" in text\n             if \"<table\" not in text:\n                 assert len(text) < 80\n \n", "problem_statement": "Client to a cluster with more than 5 workers appears as though it only has 5\n<!-- Please include a self-contained copy-pastable example that generates the issue if possible.\n\nPlease be concise with code posted. See guidelines below on how to provide a good bug report:\n\n- Craft Minimal Bug Reports http://matthewrocklin.com/blog/work/2018/02/28/minimal-bug-reports\n- Minimal Complete Verifiable Examples https://stackoverflow.com/help/mcve\n\nBug reports that follow these guidelines are easier to diagnose, and so are often handled much more quickly.\n-->\n\n**Describe the issue**: Clients only report information about the cluster's first five workers without a disclaimer.\n\n**Minimal Complete Verifiable Example**:\n\n```python\nfrom distributed import LocalCluster, Client\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    cluster = LocalCluster(n_workers=6, memory_limit=\"500MiB\")\n    c = Client(cluster)\n    print(c)\n```\n\nOutput is `<Client: 'tcp://127.0.0.1:46429' processes=5 threads=5, memory=2.44 GiB>` when it should be `processes=6 threads=6, memory=3 GiB`\n\n**Anything else we need to know?**: [This change](https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/48fcf486940a2ba4b290319e1f4355b07c91a2df) introduced this issue. cc @fjetter\n\n**Environment**:\n\n- Dask version: 2025.4.1\n- Python version: 3.11.9\n- Operating System: Linux\n- Install method (conda, pip, source): pip\n\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Thanks for the issue @zmbc. I'm able to reproduce -- https://github.com/dask/distributed/pull/9066 should fix this \n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/70367136cb32f4aee592206b0c2dd9fbade4dae9"], "created_at": "2025-05-02T15:22:32Z"}
{"repo": "dask/distributed", "pull_number": 9071, "instance_id": "dask__distributed-9071", "issue_numbers": [9070], "base_commit": "01ea1eb1a92bd1e0a30e4a9d3b438c55d2376561", "patch": "diff --git a/distributed/client.py b/distributed/client.py\nindex e758fb5bee6..19e8823eebb 100644\n--- a/distributed/client.py\n+++ b/distributed/client.py\n@@ -892,7 +892,7 @@ def _layer(self) -> dict[Key, GraphNode]:\n \n         if not self.kwargs:\n             dsk = {\n-                key: Task(key, self.func, *args)\n+                key: Task(key, self.func, *parse_input(args))  # type: ignore[misc]\n                 for key, args in zip(self.keys, zip(*self.iterables))\n             }\n \n@@ -907,12 +907,17 @@ def _layer(self) -> dict[Key, GraphNode]:\n                 else:\n                     kwargs2[k] = parse_input(v)\n \n-                dsk.update(\n-                    {\n-                        key: Task(key, self.func, *args, **kwargs2)\n-                        for key, args in zip(self.keys, zip(*self.iterables))\n-                    }\n-                )\n+            dsk.update(\n+                {\n+                    key: Task(\n+                        key,\n+                        self.func,\n+                        *parse_input(args),  # type: ignore[misc]\n+                        **kwargs2,\n+                    )\n+                    for key, args in zip(self.keys, zip(*self.iterables))\n+                }\n+            )\n         return dsk\n \n \n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/distributed/tests/test_client.py b/distributed/tests/test_client.py\nindex a4a0d0c5af2..aaf33a39e14 100644\n--- a/distributed/tests/test_client.py\n+++ b/distributed/tests/test_client.py\n@@ -8397,3 +8397,26 @@ async def test_count_serialization(c, s, a, use_lambda):\n     expected_global = expected_local + 1\n     assert x.local_count <= expected_local\n     assert x.global_count <= expected_global\n+\n+\n+@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"use_kwarg\", [False, \"simple\", \"future\"])\n+@gen_cluster(client=True)\n+async def test_map_accepts_nested_futures(c, s, a, b, use_kwarg):\n+    def reducer(futs, *, offset=0, **kwargs):\n+        return sum(futs) + offset\n+\n+    f1 = c.submit(lambda: 10)\n+    f2 = c.submit(lambda: 20)\n+    offset = None\n+    if use_kwarg == \"simple\":\n+        future = c.map(reducer, [[f1, f2]], foo=True)[0]\n+    elif use_kwarg == \"future\":\n+        offset = c.submit(lambda: 1)\n+\n+        future = c.map(reducer, [[f1, f2]], offset=offset)[0]\n+\n+    else:\n+        future = c.map(reducer, [[f1, f2]])[0]\n+\n+    result = await future.result()\n+    assert result == 30 if not offset else 31\n", "problem_statement": "PR #9008 changed how `client.map` behaves on input futures?\nI'm doing the following in my code\n```py\n            while len(work) > 1:\n                to_reduce = [work[i : i + self.treereduction] for i in range(0, len(work), self.treereduction)]\n                work = self.client.map(\n                    reducer,\n                    to_reduce,\n                    pure=True,\n                    priority=self.priority,\n                    retries=self.retries,\n                )\n\n```\nI added a `breakpoint()` right after `to_reduce` and I'm seeing this\n```\n-> work = self.client.map(\n(Pdb)\n(Pdb) to_reduce\n[[<Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-902048be-bab9-473d-bf1d-3fdac547d6de-0>, <Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-902048be-bab9-473d-bf1d-3fdac547d6de-1>]]\n```\nand the `client.map` operation succeeds.\n\nAfter https://github.com/dask/distributed/pull/9008\nI'm seeing the same type of input but the `map` fails\n```\n-> work = self.client.map(\n(Pdb)\n(Pdb) to_reduce\n[[<Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-76b97f32-a23b-4154-9f57-8b7ed16c9b30-0>, <Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-76b97f32-a23b-4154-9f57-8b7ed16c9b30-1>]]\n(Pdb) c\n[                                        ] | 0% Completed |  0.0s2025-05-07 19:28:10,614 - distributed.worker - ERROR - Compute Failed\nKey:       reduce-798319b377f9c56918c91a109edb95bb\nState:     executing\nTask:  <Task 'reduce-798319b377f9c56918c91a109edb95bb' reduce(...)>\nException: 'ValueError(\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type (<class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'> vs. <class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'>)\")'\nTraceback: '  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/executor.py\", line 240, in __call__\\n    return accumulate(items)\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 97, in accumulate\\n    accum = add(accum, next(gen))\\n            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 59, in add\\n    raise ValueError(\\n'\n\n[                                        ] | 0% Completed |  0.2s2025-05-07 19:28:10,855 - distributed.worker - ERROR - Compute Failed\nKey:       reduce-798319b377f9c56918c91a109edb95bb\nState:     executing\nTask:  <Task 'reduce-798319b377f9c56918c91a109edb95bb' reduce(...)>\nException: 'ValueError(\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type (<class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'> vs. <class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'>)\")'\nTraceback: '  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/executor.py\", line 240, in __call__\\n    return accumulate(items)\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 97, in accumulate\\n    accum = add(accum, next(gen))\\n            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 59, in add\\n    raise ValueError(\\n'\n\n[                                        ] | 0% Completed |  0.5s2025-05-07 19:28:11,099 - distributed.worker - ERROR - Compute Failed\nKey:       reduce-798319b377f9c56918c91a109edb95bb\nState:     executing\nTask:  <Task 'reduce-798319b377f9c56918c91a109edb95bb' reduce(...)>\nException: 'ValueError(\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type (<class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'> vs. <class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'>)\")'\nTraceback: '  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/executor.py\", line 240, in __call__\\n    return accumulate(items)\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 97, in accumulate\\n    accum = add(accum, next(gen))\\n            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 59, in add\\n    raise ValueError(\\n'\n\n[                                        ] | 0% Completed |  0.7s2025-05-07 19:28:11,322 - distributed.worker - ERROR - Compute Failed\nKey:       reduce-798319b377f9c56918c91a109edb95bb\nState:     executing\nTask:  <Task 'reduce-798319b377f9c56918c91a109edb95bb' reduce(...)>\nException: 'ValueError(\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type (<class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'> vs. <class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'>)\")'\nTraceback: '  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/executor.py\", line 240, in __call__\\n    return accumulate(items)\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 97, in accumulate\\n    accum = add(accum, next(gen))\\n            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 59, in add\\n    raise ValueError(\\n'\n```\n\nDid something change in how `map` behaves?\n", "hints_text": "It seems like the `reducer` function now sees `distributed.Future` inputs while before it was seeing the actual results of the futures that it can reduce?\nTo add a little more context the `reducer` is an instance of this without compression in this case.\n```py\nclass _reduce:\n    def __init__(self, compression):\n        self.compression = compression\n\n    def __str__(self):\n        return \"reduce\"\n\n    def __call__(self, items):\n        items = list(it for it in items if it is not None)\n        if len(items) == 0:\n            raise ValueError(\"Empty list provided to reduction\")\n        if self.compression is not None:\n            out = _decompress(items.pop())\n            out = accumulate(map(_decompress, items), out)\n            return _compress(out, self.compression)\n        return accumulate(items)\n```\nand indeed `accumulate` doesn't know how to `add`  `distributed.Future`s\n```py\ndef add(a: Accumulatable, b: Accumulatable) -> Accumulatable:\n    \"\"\"Add two accumulatables together, without altering inputs\n\n    This may make copies in certain situations\n    \"\"\"\n    if isinstance(a, Addable) and isinstance(b, Addable):\n        return operator.add(a, b)\n    if isinstance(a, MutableSet) and isinstance(b, MutableSet):\n        return operator.or_(a, b)\n    elif isinstance(a, MutableMapping) and isinstance(b, MutableMapping):\n        # capture type(X) by shallow copy and clear\n        # since we don't know the signature of type(X).__init__\n        if isinstance(b, type(a)):\n            out = copy.copy(a)\n        elif isinstance(a, type(b)):\n            out = copy.copy(b)\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(\n                f\"Cannot add two mappings of incompatible type ({type(a)} vs. {type(b)})\"\n            )\n        out.clear()\n        lhs, rhs = set(a), set(b)\n        # Keep the order of elements as far as possible\n        for key in a:\n            if key in rhs:\n                out[key] = add(a[key], b[key])\n            else:\n                out[key] = copy.deepcopy(a[key])\n        for key in b:\n            if key not in lhs:\n                out[key] = copy.deepcopy(b[key])\n        return out\n    raise ValueError(\n        f\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type ({type(a)} vs. {type(b)})\"\n    )\n\n\ndef iadd(a: Accumulatable, b: Accumulatable) -> Accumulatable:\n    \"\"\"Add two accumulatables together, assuming the first is mutable\"\"\"\n    if isinstance(a, Addable) and isinstance(b, Addable):\n        return operator.iadd(a, b)\n    elif isinstance(a, MutableSet) and isinstance(b, MutableSet):\n        return operator.ior(a, b)\n    elif isinstance(a, MutableMapping) and isinstance(b, MutableMapping):\n        if not isinstance(b, type(a)):\n            raise ValueError(\n                f\"Cannot add two mappings of incompatible type ({type(a)} vs. {type(b)})\"\n            )\n        lhs, rhs = set(a), set(b)\n        # Keep the order of elements as far as possible\n        for key in a:\n            if key in rhs:\n                a[key] = iadd(a[key], b[key])\n        for key in b:\n            if key not in lhs:\n                a[key] = copy.deepcopy(b[key])\n        return a\n    raise ValueError(\n        f\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type ({type(a)} vs. {type(b)})\"\n    )\n\n\ndef accumulate(\n    items: Iterable[Optional[Accumulatable]], accum: Optional[Accumulatable] = None\n) -> Optional[Accumulatable]:\n    gen = (x for x in items if x is not None)\n    try:\n        if accum is None:\n            accum = next(gen)\n            # we want to produce a new object so that the input is not mutated\n            accum = add(accum, next(gen))\n        while True:\n            # subsequent additions can happen in-place, which may be more performant\n            accum = iadd(accum, next(gen))\n    except StopIteration:\n        pass\n    return accum\n```\nbut it does know how to add `coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator` which is what the `Futures`s type is.\nA little more python debugger help\nbefore:\n```python\n-> work = self.client.map(\n(Pdb) work\n[<Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-b0bfe188-6c3e-4fe1-b374-130572e65367-0>, <Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-b0bfe188-6c3e-4fe1-b374-130572e65367-1>]\n(Pdb) self.client.map(reducer, [work])\n[<Future: pending, key: reduce-500b1391134e650a202f3f1707829e4f>]\n(Pdb) self.client.map(reducer, [work])[0].result()\nset_accumulator({<coffea.processor.executor.FileMeta object at 0x75694c754d80>, <coffea.processor.executor.FileMeta object at 0x75694c7566c0>})\n```\nafter this PR and with the latest dask/distributed.\n```py\n(Pdb) work\n[<Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-078e8ea2-cd64-41c3-b1ae-69a1443ce050-0>, <Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-078e8ea2-cd64-41c3-b1ae-69a1443ce050-1>]\n(Pdb) self.client.map(reducer, [work])\n[<Future: pending, key: reduce-dcc4017cfcaccf00fc8169cf1cd8d757>]\n(Pdb) self.client.map(reducer, [work])[0].result()\n2025-05-07 22:14:48,862 - distributed.worker - ERROR - Compute Failed\nKey:       reduce-dcc4017cfcaccf00fc8169cf1cd8d757\nState:     executing\nTask:  <Task 'reduce-dcc4017cfcaccf00fc8169cf1cd8d757' reduce(...)>\nException: 'ValueError(\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type (<class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'> vs. <class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'>)\")'\nTraceback: '  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/executor.py\", line 240, in __call__\\n    return accumulate(items)\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 97, in accumulate\\n    accum = add(accum, next(gen))\\n            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 59, in add\\n    raise ValueError(\\n'\n\n*** ValueError: Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type (<class 'distributed.client.Future'> vs. <class 'distributed.client.Future'>)\n```\nIn previous versions the `add` function sees `Addable` stuff and goes down this path\n```py\n    if isinstance(a, Addable) and isinstance(b, Addable):\n        return operator.add(a, b)\n```\nIn latest dask/distributed > 2025.3.0 it sees `distributed.Future` and goes down the else path and errors\n```py\n    raise ValueError(\n        f\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type ({type(a)} vs. {type(b)})\"\n    )\n```\nSo the way I see it is that the inputs to `client.map` were gathered before passed inside the mappable function when asking for the result while now they are passed inside the function as is?\nMinimal reproducer\n```py\n#!/usr/bin/env python3\nfrom dask.distributed import Client\n\ndef reducer(futs):\n    # futs is a list of two futures; simply add them\n    a, b = futs\n    return a + b\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    client = Client()\n\n    # create two simple futures\n    f1 = client.submit(lambda: 10)\n    f2 = client.submit(lambda: 20)\n\n    work = [f1, f2]\n\n    # Map our reducer over a single element list [work]\n    # i.e. reducer will get passed the list [f1,f2]\n    future = client.map(reducer, [work])[0]\n\n    # In older distributed: .result() \u2192 30\n    # In newer   distributed: raises the incompatible\u2010type error\n    print(\"Result:\", future.result())\n```\nerrors with\n```\n2025-05-07 22:33:25,478 - distributed.worker - ERROR - Compute Failed\nKey:       reducer-5d64c031c40b294fb2d28b8ffb75622b\nState:     executing\nTask:  <Task 'reducer-5d64c031c40b294fb2d28b8ffb75622b' reducer(...)>\nException: 'TypeError(\"unsupported operand type(s) for +: \\'Future\\' and \\'Future\\'\")'\nTraceback: '  File \"<ipython-input-1-e924ebcfeaae>\", line 7, in reducer\\n'\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nTypeError                                 Traceback (most recent call last)\nCell In[1], line 24\n     20 future = client.map(reducer, [work])[0]\n     22 # In older distributed: .result() \u2192 30\n     23 # In newer   distributed: may raise the incompatible\u2010type error\n---> 24 print(\"Result:\", future.result())\n\nFile ~/miniforge3/envs/higgs-dna/lib/python3.11/site-packages/distributed/client.py:392, in Future.result(self, timeout)\n    390 self._verify_initialized()\n    391 with shorten_traceback():\n--> 392     return self.client.sync(self._result, callback_timeout=timeout)\n\nCell In[1], line 7, in reducer()\n      4 def reducer(futs):\n      5     # futs is a list of two futures; simply add them\n      6     a, b = futs\n----> 7     return a + b\n\nTypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for +: 'Future' and 'Future'\n```\nWhile with dask/distributed 2025.3.0 it works.\n\ncc @fjetter \n\n", "all_hints_text": "It seems like the `reducer` function now sees `distributed.Future` inputs while before it was seeing the actual results of the futures that it can reduce?\nTo add a little more context the `reducer` is an instance of this without compression in this case.\n```py\nclass _reduce:\n    def __init__(self, compression):\n        self.compression = compression\n\n    def __str__(self):\n        return \"reduce\"\n\n    def __call__(self, items):\n        items = list(it for it in items if it is not None)\n        if len(items) == 0:\n            raise ValueError(\"Empty list provided to reduction\")\n        if self.compression is not None:\n            out = _decompress(items.pop())\n            out = accumulate(map(_decompress, items), out)\n            return _compress(out, self.compression)\n        return accumulate(items)\n```\nand indeed `accumulate` doesn't know how to `add`  `distributed.Future`s\n```py\ndef add(a: Accumulatable, b: Accumulatable) -> Accumulatable:\n    \"\"\"Add two accumulatables together, without altering inputs\n\n    This may make copies in certain situations\n    \"\"\"\n    if isinstance(a, Addable) and isinstance(b, Addable):\n        return operator.add(a, b)\n    if isinstance(a, MutableSet) and isinstance(b, MutableSet):\n        return operator.or_(a, b)\n    elif isinstance(a, MutableMapping) and isinstance(b, MutableMapping):\n        # capture type(X) by shallow copy and clear\n        # since we don't know the signature of type(X).__init__\n        if isinstance(b, type(a)):\n            out = copy.copy(a)\n        elif isinstance(a, type(b)):\n            out = copy.copy(b)\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(\n                f\"Cannot add two mappings of incompatible type ({type(a)} vs. {type(b)})\"\n            )\n        out.clear()\n        lhs, rhs = set(a), set(b)\n        # Keep the order of elements as far as possible\n        for key in a:\n            if key in rhs:\n                out[key] = add(a[key], b[key])\n            else:\n                out[key] = copy.deepcopy(a[key])\n        for key in b:\n            if key not in lhs:\n                out[key] = copy.deepcopy(b[key])\n        return out\n    raise ValueError(\n        f\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type ({type(a)} vs. {type(b)})\"\n    )\n\n\ndef iadd(a: Accumulatable, b: Accumulatable) -> Accumulatable:\n    \"\"\"Add two accumulatables together, assuming the first is mutable\"\"\"\n    if isinstance(a, Addable) and isinstance(b, Addable):\n        return operator.iadd(a, b)\n    elif isinstance(a, MutableSet) and isinstance(b, MutableSet):\n        return operator.ior(a, b)\n    elif isinstance(a, MutableMapping) and isinstance(b, MutableMapping):\n        if not isinstance(b, type(a)):\n            raise ValueError(\n                f\"Cannot add two mappings of incompatible type ({type(a)} vs. {type(b)})\"\n            )\n        lhs, rhs = set(a), set(b)\n        # Keep the order of elements as far as possible\n        for key in a:\n            if key in rhs:\n                a[key] = iadd(a[key], b[key])\n        for key in b:\n            if key not in lhs:\n                a[key] = copy.deepcopy(b[key])\n        return a\n    raise ValueError(\n        f\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type ({type(a)} vs. {type(b)})\"\n    )\n\n\ndef accumulate(\n    items: Iterable[Optional[Accumulatable]], accum: Optional[Accumulatable] = None\n) -> Optional[Accumulatable]:\n    gen = (x for x in items if x is not None)\n    try:\n        if accum is None:\n            accum = next(gen)\n            # we want to produce a new object so that the input is not mutated\n            accum = add(accum, next(gen))\n        while True:\n            # subsequent additions can happen in-place, which may be more performant\n            accum = iadd(accum, next(gen))\n    except StopIteration:\n        pass\n    return accum\n```\nbut it does know how to add `coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator` which is what the `Futures`s type is.\nA little more python debugger help\nbefore:\n```python\n-> work = self.client.map(\n(Pdb) work\n[<Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-b0bfe188-6c3e-4fe1-b374-130572e65367-0>, <Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-b0bfe188-6c3e-4fe1-b374-130572e65367-1>]\n(Pdb) self.client.map(reducer, [work])\n[<Future: pending, key: reduce-500b1391134e650a202f3f1707829e4f>]\n(Pdb) self.client.map(reducer, [work])[0].result()\nset_accumulator({<coffea.processor.executor.FileMeta object at 0x75694c754d80>, <coffea.processor.executor.FileMeta object at 0x75694c7566c0>})\n```\nafter this PR and with the latest dask/distributed.\n```py\n(Pdb) work\n[<Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-078e8ea2-cd64-41c3-b1ae-69a1443ce050-0>, <Future: finished, type: coffea.processor.accumulator.set_accumulator, key: automatic_retries-078e8ea2-cd64-41c3-b1ae-69a1443ce050-1>]\n(Pdb) self.client.map(reducer, [work])\n[<Future: pending, key: reduce-dcc4017cfcaccf00fc8169cf1cd8d757>]\n(Pdb) self.client.map(reducer, [work])[0].result()\n2025-05-07 22:14:48,862 - distributed.worker - ERROR - Compute Failed\nKey:       reduce-dcc4017cfcaccf00fc8169cf1cd8d757\nState:     executing\nTask:  <Task 'reduce-dcc4017cfcaccf00fc8169cf1cd8d757' reduce(...)>\nException: 'ValueError(\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type (<class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'> vs. <class \\'distributed.client.Future\\'>)\")'\nTraceback: '  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/executor.py\", line 240, in __call__\\n    return accumulate(items)\\n           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 97, in accumulate\\n    accum = add(accum, next(gen))\\n            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\\n  File \"/home/iason/software/coffea/coffea/processor/accumulator.py\", line 59, in add\\n    raise ValueError(\\n'\n\n*** ValueError: Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type (<class 'distributed.client.Future'> vs. <class 'distributed.client.Future'>)\n```\nIn previous versions the `add` function sees `Addable` stuff and goes down this path\n```py\n    if isinstance(a, Addable) and isinstance(b, Addable):\n        return operator.add(a, b)\n```\nIn latest dask/distributed > 2025.3.0 it sees `distributed.Future` and goes down the else path and errors\n```py\n    raise ValueError(\n        f\"Cannot add accumulators of incompatible type ({type(a)} vs. {type(b)})\"\n    )\n```\nSo the way I see it is that the inputs to `client.map` were gathered before passed inside the mappable function when asking for the result while now they are passed inside the function as is?\nMinimal reproducer\n```py\n#!/usr/bin/env python3\nfrom dask.distributed import Client\n\ndef reducer(futs):\n    # futs is a list of two futures; simply add them\n    a, b = futs\n    return a + b\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    client = Client()\n\n    # create two simple futures\n    f1 = client.submit(lambda: 10)\n    f2 = client.submit(lambda: 20)\n\n    work = [f1, f2]\n\n    # Map our reducer over a single element list [work]\n    # i.e. reducer will get passed the list [f1,f2]\n    future = client.map(reducer, [work])[0]\n\n    # In older distributed: .result() \u2192 30\n    # In newer   distributed: raises the incompatible\u2010type error\n    print(\"Result:\", future.result())\n```\nerrors with\n```\n2025-05-07 22:33:25,478 - distributed.worker - ERROR - Compute Failed\nKey:       reducer-5d64c031c40b294fb2d28b8ffb75622b\nState:     executing\nTask:  <Task 'reducer-5d64c031c40b294fb2d28b8ffb75622b' reducer(...)>\nException: 'TypeError(\"unsupported operand type(s) for +: \\'Future\\' and \\'Future\\'\")'\nTraceback: '  File \"<ipython-input-1-e924ebcfeaae>\", line 7, in reducer\\n'\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nTypeError                                 Traceback (most recent call last)\nCell In[1], line 24\n     20 future = client.map(reducer, [work])[0]\n     22 # In older distributed: .result() \u2192 30\n     23 # In newer   distributed: may raise the incompatible\u2010type error\n---> 24 print(\"Result:\", future.result())\n\nFile ~/miniforge3/envs/higgs-dna/lib/python3.11/site-packages/distributed/client.py:392, in Future.result(self, timeout)\n    390 self._verify_initialized()\n    391 with shorten_traceback():\n--> 392     return self.client.sync(self._result, callback_timeout=timeout)\n\nCell In[1], line 7, in reducer()\n      4 def reducer(futs):\n      5     # futs is a list of two futures; simply add them\n      6     a, b = futs\n----> 7     return a + b\n\nTypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for +: 'Future' and 'Future'\n```\nWhile with dask/distributed 2025.3.0 it works.\n\ncc @fjetter \nthanks for the reproducer. see https://github.com/dask/distributed/pull/9071\nThanks @fjetter for the quick fix.\n\nJust one question for my understanding, what I tried doing in https://github.com/scikit-hep/coffea/pull/1322 to overcome this, which is basically loop over the inputs and do `client.submit` instead of `client.map` without the loop, are those equivalent? Does the `client.map` do some optimizations that are better than a for loop?\n>  Does the client.map do some optimizations that are better than a for loop?\n\nFunctionally, both is/should be equivalent. `map` will be faster since it submits everything at once (this also eliminates the possibility of race conditions if you have a more complex setup). Particularly for a large number of tasks the submission overhead can be quite noticeable. \nGot it, so there is a submission delay because you submit in a loop instead of all at once but the actual computation time of the futures should be identical. Thanks!\nYeah, there are also some shananigans about serialization, e.g. if your function or the arguments are expensive to serialize, you'll also be better off in terms of memory utilization on the scheduler... but that's details. For most users this isn't relevant\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/140f78e4592c13561f171985e88c4d1265da576f"], "created_at": "2025-05-08T14:04:38Z"}
{"repo": "dask/distributed", "pull_number": 9085, "instance_id": "dask__distributed-9085", "issue_numbers": [9080], "base_commit": "801d0ed73649e654e7111d0208d0f6fcacf47acb", "patch": "diff --git a/distributed/client.py b/distributed/client.py\nindex 19e8823eebb..12d7c7d6448 100644\n--- a/distributed/client.py\n+++ b/distributed/client.py\n@@ -355,7 +355,10 @@ def status(self):\n         str\n             The status\n         \"\"\"\n-        return self._state.status\n+        if self._state:\n+            return self._state.status\n+        else:\n+            return None\n \n     def done(self):\n         \"\"\"Returns whether or not the computation completed.\n@@ -554,7 +557,10 @@ def traceback(self, timeout=None, **kwargs):\n     @property\n     def type(self):\n         \"\"\"Returns the type\"\"\"\n-        return self._state.type\n+        if self._state:\n+            return self._state.type\n+        else:\n+            return None\n \n     def release(self):\n         \"\"\"\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "`test_resubmit_nondeterministic_task_different_deps` fails consistently on CI\n<img width=\"935\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/296bc49f-6a89-490d-a132-2184cb5dcafb\" />\n", "hints_text": "Okay, so it looks like https://github.com/dask/dask/pull/11945 (note, that's a `dask/dask` change, not a `dask/distributed` change) is when this test started failing \n\n", "all_hints_text": "Okay, so it looks like https://github.com/dask/dask/pull/11945 (note, that's a `dask/dask` change, not a `dask/distributed` change) is when this test started failing \n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/3ad943c9b7e0d69e223985072c26ba087a5b0cc4"], "created_at": "2025-06-02T19:26:38Z"}
{"repo": "dask/distributed", "pull_number": 9123, "instance_id": "dask__distributed-9123", "issue_numbers": [9099], "base_commit": "c9e7aca18e267cf18b34070afedf0348589f14ea", "patch": "diff --git a/distributed/client.py b/distributed/client.py\nindex 01fe47fa9cf..e778e5da29c 100644\n--- a/distributed/client.py\n+++ b/distributed/client.py\n@@ -31,9 +31,11 @@\n     Any,\n     Callable,\n     ClassVar,\n+    Generic,\n     Literal,\n     NamedTuple,\n     TypedDict,\n+    TypeVar,\n     cast,\n )\n \n@@ -138,6 +140,8 @@\n \n TOPIC_PREFIX_FORWARDED_LOG_RECORD = \"forwarded-log-record\"\n \n+_T = TypeVar(\"_T\")\n+\n \n class FutureCancelledError(CancelledError):\n     key: str\n@@ -241,7 +245,7 @@ def _del_global_client(c: Client) -> None:\n             pass\n \n \n-class Future(TaskRef):\n+class Future(TaskRef, Generic[_T]):\n     \"\"\"A remotely running computation\n \n     A Future is a local proxy to a result running on a remote worker.  A user\n@@ -371,7 +375,7 @@ def done(self):\n         \"\"\"\n         return self._state.done()\n \n-    def result(self, timeout=None):\n+    def result(self, timeout=None) -> _T:\n         \"\"\"Wait until computation completes, gather result to local process.\n \n         Parameters\n@@ -2033,7 +2037,7 @@ def get_executor(self, **kwargs):\n \n     def submit(\n         self,\n-        func,\n+        func: Callable[..., _T],\n         *args,\n         key=None,\n         workers=None,\n@@ -2046,7 +2050,7 @@ def submit(\n         actors=False,\n         pure=True,\n         **kwargs,\n-    ):\n+    ) -> Future[_T]:\n         \"\"\"Submit a function application to the scheduler\n \n         Parameters\n@@ -2154,7 +2158,7 @@ def submit(\n                     key,\n                     func,\n                     *(parse_input(a) for a in args),\n-                    **{k: parse_input(v) for k, v in kwargs.items()},\n+                    **{k: parse_input(v) for k, v in kwargs.items()},  # type: ignore\n                 )\n             },\n             # We'd like to avoid hashing/tokenizing all of the above.\n@@ -2181,7 +2185,7 @@ def submit(\n \n     def map(\n         self,\n-        func: Callable,\n+        func: Callable[..., _T],\n         *iterables: Collection,\n         key: str | list | None = None,\n         workers: str | Iterable[str] | None = None,\n@@ -2195,7 +2199,7 @@ def map(\n         pure: bool = True,\n         batch_size=None,\n         **kwargs,\n-    ):\n+    ) -> list[Future[_T]]:\n         \"\"\"Map a function on a sequence of arguments\n \n         Arguments can be normal objects or Futures\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Typing for `map`, `submit` and `Future`\nIn `concurrent.future` [typeshed](https://github.com/python/typeshed/blob/main/stdlib/concurrent/futures/_base.pyi), `Executor.map` and `Executor.submit` return a typed `Future[T]`. This is very nice for hinting in the IDE. Would it be possible to add this to `dask.distributed`?\n\nSomething along the following lines:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import Callable, Generic, ParamSpec, TypeVar\n\n_T = TypeVar(\"_T\")\n_P = ParamSpec(\"_P\") # ParamSpec was introduced in 3.10.\n\n\nclass Future(TaskRef, Generic[_T]):\n    def result(self, timeout=None) -> _T:\n        ...\n\nclass Client(SyncMethodMixin):\n    def submit(\n        self,\n        func: Callable[_P, _T],\n        *args: _P.args,\n        key=None,\n        workers=None,\n        resources=None,\n        retries=None,\n        priority=0,\n        fifo_timeout=\"100 ms\",\n        allow_other_workers=False,\n        actor=False,\n        actors=False,\n        pure=True,\n        **kwargs: _P.kwargs,\n    ) -> Future[_T]:\n        ...\n\n    def map(\n        self,\n        func: Callable[..., _T],\n        *iterables: Collection,\n        key: str | list | None = None,\n        workers: str | Iterable[str] | None = None,\n        retries: int | None = None,\n        resources: dict[str, Any] | None = None,\n        priority: int = 0,\n        allow_other_workers: bool = False,\n        fifo_timeout: str = \"100 ms\",\n        actor: bool = False,\n        actors: bool = False,\n        pure: bool = True,\n        batch_size=None,\n        **kwargs,\n    ) -> list[Future[_T]]:\n        ...\n\nc = Client()\nf = c.submit(lambda x: 0, 1)\n# Revealed type is \"mock.Future[builtins.int]\"\nfutures = c.map(lambda x: 0, [1, 2, 3])\n# Revealed type is \"builtins.list[mock.Future[builtins.int]]\"\n```\n\n`map` would need some more work because the types of `*iterables*` will be hard to distribute to the different parameters of `func`. It might make sense to use an `@overload` for the simple case of only one iterable (and maybe additional ones for two and three to cover the most common cases).\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/4df69bcd8ce84c618b4b8d7cb44e3cedf47cf9e1", "https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/81fe1e2545061935c08d2f20ce4c47c24f8a7957"], "created_at": "2025-10-10T10:08:31Z"}
{"repo": "dask/distributed", "pull_number": 9111, "instance_id": "dask__distributed-9111", "issue_numbers": [9110], "base_commit": "7024d521bb2947bd4a8a713648b2e41b134f98b5", "patch": "diff --git a/continuous_integration/environment-3.10.yaml b/continuous_integration/environment-3.10.yaml\nindex e35a5046424..c1f45fc7f28 100644\n--- a/continuous_integration/environment-3.10.yaml\n+++ b/continuous_integration/environment-3.10.yaml\n@@ -32,7 +32,7 @@ dependencies:\n   - prometheus_client\n   - psutil\n   - pyarrow\n-  - pynvml  # Only tested here\n+  - nvidia-ml-py  # Only tested here\n   - pytest<8.4  # Pin due to https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest-cov/issues/693\n   - pytest-cov\n   - pytest-faulthandler\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "pynvml warning causing CI failure\nCI is failing with pynvml errors https://github.com/dask/distributed/actions/runs/17616908367/job/50052323428?pr=9109\n\n```\nERROR: while parsing the following warning configuration:\n\n  ignore::distributed.versions.VersionMismatchWarning\n\nThis error occurred:\n\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"/home/runner/miniconda3/envs/dask-distributed/lib/python3.10/site-packages/_pytest/config/__init__.py\", line 1918, in parse_warning_filter\nWarning: ory: type[Warning] = _resolve_warning_category(category_)\n  File \"/home/runner/miniconda3/envs/dask-distributed/lib/python3.10/site-packages/_pytest/config/__init__.py\", line 1956, in _resolve_warning_category\n    m = __import__(module, None, None, [klass])\n  File \"/home/runner/work/distributed/distributed/distributed/__init__.py\", line 23, in <module>\n    from distributed.actor import Actor, ActorFuture, BaseActorFuture\n  File \"/home/runner/work/distributed/distributed/distributed/actor.py\", line 15, in <module>\n    from distributed.client import Future\n  File \"/home/runner/work/distributed/distributed/distributed/client.py\", line 65, in <module>\n    from distributed import cluster_dump, preloading\n  File \"/home/runner/work/distributed/distributed/distributed/preloading.py\", line 18, in <module>\n    from distributed.core import Server\n  File \"/home/runner/work/distributed/distributed/distributed/core.py\", line 53, in <module>\n    from distributed.system_monitor import SystemMonitor\n  File \"/home/runner/work/distributed/distributed/distributed/system_monitor.py\", line 14, in <module>\n    from distributed.diagnostics import nvml\n  File \"/home/runner/work/distributed/distributed/distributed/diagnostics/nvml.py\", line 14, in <module>\n    import pynvml\n  File \"<frozen importlib._bootstrap>\", line 1027, in _find_and_load\n  File \"<frozen importlib._bootstrap>\", line 1002, in _find_and_load_unlocked\n  File \"<frozen importlib._bootstrap>\", line 945, in _find_spec\n  File \"/home/runner/miniconda3/envs/dask-distributed/lib/python3.10/site-packages/_pynvml_redirector.py\", line 29, in find_spec\n    warnings.warn(PYNVML_MSG, FutureWarning, stacklevel=2)\nFutureWarning: The pynvml package is deprecated. Please install nvidia-ml-py instead. If you did not install pynvml directly, please report this to the maintainers of the package that installed pynvml for you.\n```\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/d1b3be8bdef934e30eb2c426f6ac4dcafd409eba"], "created_at": "2025-09-10T14:35:34Z"}
{"repo": "dask/distributed", "pull_number": 9120, "instance_id": "dask__distributed-9120", "issue_numbers": [9112], "base_commit": "8e604a0136c67e374d5ec96c433ade80867615eb", "patch": "diff --git a/distributed/worker.py b/distributed/worker.py\nindex e68a77894c2..7e3c01ba5c5 100644\n--- a/distributed/worker.py\n+++ b/distributed/worker.py\n@@ -647,10 +647,15 @@ def __init__(\n         if scheduler_sni:\n             self.connection_args[\"server_hostname\"] = scheduler_sni\n \n+        self.name = name\n+\n+        executor_pool_prefix = f\"{self.name}-\" if self.name else \"\"\n         # Common executors always available\n         self.executors = {\n             \"offload\": utils._offload_executor,\n-            \"actor\": ThreadPoolExecutor(1, thread_name_prefix=\"Dask-Actor-Threads\"),\n+            \"actor\": ThreadPoolExecutor(\n+                1, thread_name_prefix=f\"{executor_pool_prefix}Dask-Actor-Threads\"\n+            ),\n         }\n \n         # Find the default executor\n@@ -660,13 +665,14 @@ def __init__(\n             self.executors.update(executor)\n         elif executor is not None:\n             self.executors[\"default\"] = executor\n+\n         if \"default\" not in self.executors:\n             self.executors[\"default\"] = ThreadPoolExecutor(\n-                nthreads, thread_name_prefix=\"Dask-Default-Threads\"\n+                nthreads,\n+                thread_name_prefix=f\"{executor_pool_prefix}Dask-Default-Threads\",\n             )\n \n         self.batched_stream = BatchedSend(interval=\"2ms\", loop=self.loop)\n-        self.name = name\n         self.scheduler_delay = 0\n         self.stream_comms = {}\n \n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/distributed/tests/test_worker.py b/distributed/tests/test_worker.py\nindex 6d1946570df..acca4423416 100644\n--- a/distributed/tests/test_worker.py\n+++ b/distributed/tests/test_worker.py\n@@ -2148,6 +2148,31 @@ def get_thread_name():\n         assert \"Dask-Foo-Threads\" in gpu_result\n \n \n+@gen_cluster(client=True, nthreads=[])\n+async def test_executor_inherit_threadname_from_worker(c, s):\n+    def get_thread_name():\n+        return threading.current_thread().name\n+\n+    async with Worker(\n+        s.address,\n+        nthreads=1,\n+        name=\"WorkerName\",\n+    ):\n+        result = await c.gather(c.submit(get_thread_name, pure=False))\n+        assert \"WorkerName-Dask-Default-Threads\" in result\n+\n+    async with Worker(\n+        s.address,\n+        nthreads=1,\n+        name=\"ALongWorkerNameThatNoOneWillProbablyEverAssignButThisTestsTheRobustnessOfLogic\",\n+    ):\n+        result = await c.gather(c.submit(get_thread_name, pure=False))\n+        assert (\n+            \"ALongWorkerNameThatNoOneWillProbablyEverAssignButThisTestsTheRobustnessOfLogic-Dask-Default-Threads\"\n+            in result\n+        )\n+\n+\n @gen_cluster(client=True)\n async def test_bad_executor_annotation(c, s, a, b):\n     with dask.annotate(executor=\"bad\"):\n", "problem_statement": "Allow renaming worker ThreadPool's thread_name_prefix from worker parameters\nThe [distributed ThreadPoolExecutor](https://github.com/dask/distributed/blob/main/distributed/threadpoolexecutor.py#L86-L91) sets the name of each thread based on thread_name_prefix parameter.\n\nThe dask worker, by default, passes a fixed name `Dask-Default-Threads` as the `thread_name_prefix` \n[Corresponding code in dask worker which sets name](https://github.com/dask/distributed/blob/main/distributed/worker.py#L663-L666)\n\nDask's worker parameters only allow [overriding the executor](https://github.com/dask/distributed/blob/main/distributed/worker.py#L380-L388), but since `executor` has to be an instance of some `Executor` (i.e. its a python object), we can't pass this object from outside of python,\nfor example, when passing \"worker json spec\" to the `dask spec` command to start a worker.\n\nIf we can allow user to override this thread_name_prefix of the default executor, by adding one more parameter in the worker params which accepts a string, that would be useful.\n\nAlso on another note, the default name of the worker threadpool, can be derived from the worker's `self.name` attribute itself, rather than always defaulting to `Dask-Default-Threads`\n", "hints_text": "I would be happy to raise MR for this. But I would like to know which approach will be better.\n1. Add a new parameter to `Worker` to override threadpool name\n2. Use the `worker.name` to generate the default threadpool name, like `{worker.name}-Thread`\n3. Do both 1 and 2\n\nI don't have any strong feelings either way.\n\nSomeone else might chime in here later, but I would suggest you move forward with whichever approach would be most helpful to you as a user.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "I would be happy to raise MR for this. But I would like to know which approach will be better.\n1. Add a new parameter to `Worker` to override threadpool name\n2. Use the `worker.name` to generate the default threadpool name, like `{worker.name}-Thread`\n3. Do both 1 and 2\n\nI don't have any strong feelings either way.\n\nSomeone else might chime in here later, but I would suggest you move forward with whichever approach would be most helpful to you as a user.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/5df818a30e9cb35382ce3507c78e3f2a6cd53c49", "https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/e433592d930d17db0eb7229a35228db28b20ff4e"], "created_at": "2025-09-30T18:03:20Z"}
{"repo": "dask/distributed", "pull_number": 9136, "instance_id": "dask__distributed-9136", "issue_numbers": [9135], "base_commit": "1ee4756b97cd1cd5c074c40b2057d31613fe1ab9", "patch": "diff --git a/continuous_integration/condarc b/continuous_integration/condarc\nindex 258ac5fa5db..609865a7a5f 100644\n--- a/continuous_integration/condarc\n+++ b/continuous_integration/condarc\n@@ -2,7 +2,6 @@ channels:\n   - conda-forge\n   - defaults\n channel_priority: true\n-auto_activate_base: false\n remote_backoff_factor: 20\n remote_connect_timeout_secs: 20.0\n remote_max_retries: 10\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Conda environment setup is failing in CI\n```\n  MultipleKeysError: Multiple aliased keys in file /Users/runner/.condarc:\n    - auto_activate\n    - auto_activate_base\n  Must declare only one. Prefer 'auto_activate'\n```\n\nExample run https://github.com/dask/distributed/actions/runs/19034696018/job/54356093524?pr=9133\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/dask/distributed/commit/82254685f4ec38b781fdc486037a2b4ae50cede5"], "created_at": "2025-11-03T13:59:17Z"}
